    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2589090193" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2589090193" />
    <a title="Jocelin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5896693-jocelin"><img alt="Jocelin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1311796949p2/5896693.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2589090193?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jocelin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jocelin" href="/user/show/5896693-jocelin">Jocelin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2589090193" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16352862405506754031">I can&apos;t remember the last time I gave a book 1 star, because I generally don&apos;t finish a book that I find to be that terrible. And let me be very clear: this book is terrible. I had to force myself to read the entire thing, and took breaks when the absurdity of it all was too much. <br/><br/>This review is filled with spoilers for everyone who found this book as insulting to the franchise as I did. I have watched every episode of MSW, all 4 made-for-TV movies, and read every book in this series. The new au</span>
  <span id="freeText16352862405506754031" style="display:none">I can't remember the last time I gave a book 1 star, because I generally don't finish a book that I find to be that terrible. And let me be very clear: this book is terrible. I had to force myself to read the entire thing, and took breaks when the absurdity of it all was too much. <br /><br />This review is filled with spoilers for everyone who found this book as insulting to the franchise as I did. I have watched every episode of MSW, all 4 made-for-TV movies, and read every book in this series. The new author appears to have little to no knowledge of who Jessica Fletcher is, and the backstory and characters in her world. To begin with, any casual fan knows that Jessica's longtime publisher is Vaughn Buckley, and not Lane Barfield.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ The tone of the book, and the language used reads like a cheap thriller, or an underdeveloped Dan Brown novel. (For the record, I like Dan Brown.) Jessica does not sound or speak like the eloquent, sophisticated Jessica we know, she sounds and speaks like a crass, bitter, jaded, sarcastic PI making off-color jokes with the occasional curse word thrown in for good measure: "nobody squealed", "pain in the ass", "any chance of you getting Somerville to let me interview Francis Malloy?"<br /><br />The other staple characters like Mort, Seth and Artie aren't themselves either: they are crass, rude, sarcastic and make fun of Jessica. They aren't her friends, and don't treat her well. It's bizarre. Jessica questions if Mort has ever drawn a gun (we know he is retired NYPD - does the author not know what that means?), and Mort actually lies to the FBI in the story, when he's not hanging up on Jessica. Not believable or inline with his character at all. And there is no way that Artie would reveal the name and location of someone in the witness protection program to Jessica, even if his safety had been compromised.<br /><br />The book is more violent and graphic then any other story has been: characters are disposable, there are descriptions of bleeding, shootouts, and acts of violence left and right. Jessica's house burns down (!), and she's barely sentimental about her late husband's belongings going up in flames. There are also 2 unnecessary mentions of dogs dying, in case the violence against people wasn't enough.<br /><br />There are so many references to things that Jessica does that are out of character, it's such lazy character research: It's joked that Jessica doesn't know how to cook, and hates winter (she chooses to live in Maine!). Jessica casually calls the First Lady on her cell phone and manages to score a meeting with the President where she says basically nothing. Jessica takes a regional train from NY to Boston? There is no way she wouldn't be on the Acela, why make that trip longer than necessary? In the beginning Jessica's character spends so much time commenting on how nice a random chain bakery is that I am convinced it was a paid placement.<br /><br />Lastly, in case it wasn't obvious that this story about a woman was written by a man, with a man's perspective, he has Jessica carrying around nail polish in her purse, and the First Lady running away with a designer handbag that contains a bottle of perfume. Um, no. Just no.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I am deeply disappointed. Donald Bain worked so hard to keep this series fun and fresh, and it's falling to pieces without him.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16352862405506754031" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


