  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2594375823" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2594375823" />
    <a title="Jay" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45415801-jay"><img alt="Jay" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611504191p2/45415801.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2594375823?book_show_action=true">Nov 17, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jay" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jay" href="/user/show/45415801-jay">Jay</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2594375823" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14139211197556972964">As much as I loved the first Murder, She Wrote story that author Jon Land had a hand in creating, his second (and first solo credited) stab at continuing the adventures of everyone&apos;s favorite busybody/mystery writer Jessica Fletcher is a grand slam of writing entertainment and surpasses the first book.<br/><br/>When an old writing acquaintance, down on his luck, tells Jessica that the publisher they shared has been stealing money from them, she is at first disbelieving. But she starts to grow suspicious w</span>
  <span id="freeText14139211197556972964" style="display:none">As much as I loved the first Murder, She Wrote story that author Jon Land had a hand in creating, his second (and first solo credited) stab at continuing the adventures of everyone's favorite busybody/mystery writer Jessica Fletcher is a grand slam of writing entertainment and surpasses the first book.<br /><br />When an old writing acquaintance, down on his luck, tells Jessica that the publisher they shared has been stealing money from them, she is at first disbelieving. But she starts to grow suspicious when the man turns up dead in what appears to be a suicide. But soon it looks more like a murder. <br /><br />But when she approaches said publisher, Lane Barfield, she says nothing and instead is handed a manuscript from an unknown author that he's excited about. He wants Jessica to read it and consider doing a blurb for it. Jessica takes the book with every intention of doing so but when Barfield turns up dead, the already sinister atmosphere turns even darker.<br /><br />As is her standard procedure, Jessica ends up looking into the seemingly random deaths. And she learns that there has been other deaths, all apparently tied to the book that is now in her possession. <br /><br />The book is an action thriller about a conspiracy involving the child of a sitting president and what she hears that marks her for death. It's not what Jessica would consider something she'd normally read but she can't help but be captivated by the tale. That is until there's an attempt to kill her and steal the manuscript. <br /><br />The game is now afoot, as they say, because Fletcher is now even more motivated to find out what is going on. This path leads her straight to the White House. Could the book be more than a fictional tale? Who is the mysteriously unknown author that wrote the book? And why does everyone who reads the book become a corpse?<br /><br />As a longtime fan of Jon Land's thrillers, this book had all the earmarks of one of those fast paced and electrifyingly paced books. You might think that combining that with the more cozy aspects of the Murder, She Wrote storytelling would make for a hard mix of differing story telling methods but this works almost entirely too well. In Land's hands, he makes Jessica kind of a bad-ass. <br /><br />No, not like some pistol packing action hero, but certainly far more actively involved in an action thriller than you'd ever expect from a senior citizen snoop like what you remember of Jessica Fletcher from the TV series.<br /><br />The book within a book is called "The Affair" and I have to say that the excerpts that Jessica was "reading" in this story had me wishing Land would write that tale in and of itself. <br /><br />The exasperated but loyal supporting cast had some great little moments as well as some well-timed humorous reactions and dialogue dealing with Jessica's longstanding ability to insinuate herself into murder investigations.<br /><br />No pun intended but "Manuscript For Murder" was a killer read and I'm loving what Jon Land is doing with the series so far.<br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14139211197556972964" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

